description: Little oil-slick dinosaurs stomping around the park! In the trees above, a loud mixed blackbird flock of grackles and red-wings, but just these guys on the ground and easily visible at the time. Sparrows hop along the ground, robins run, and grackles STALK, very tall and deliberate, and the pale eyes add to the menacing mini velociraptor impression. Super glossy and iridescent, so these are probably all males, but I have read that in some local varieties the females are less brown and nearly as shiny, so not necessarily a slam dunk. I wanted to try and record the stereotypical “rusty gate” calls to post a sound clip observation, but the ones in the bushes who were singing kept hushing up whenever I would press record on my phone. I’ll get them eventually…

Red-winged Blackbird - Order Passeriformes : Family Icteridae : Agelaius phoeniceus There are 22 recognized subspecies.

The Red-winged Blackbird, easily recognizable by its distinctive call, breeds from Alaska to Newfoundland, south to Florida and into Mexico and Guatamala. There are also isolated populations in western El Salvador, northwestern Honduras and northwestern Costa Rica.

The red and yellow on the wing is only present in the male. The female is a non-descript dark brown. A common bird, during the breeding season they will divebomb anyone who happens to walk anywhere near their nest making a stroll in the park rather interesting.

The bird was near the pond in the center of Rosehill Cemetery in Chicago. It's breeding season for the species and there are a lot of reeds around making it a perfect place for them to build their nest.

description: Little oil-slick dinosaurs stomping around the park! In the trees above, a loud mixed blackbird flock of grackles and red-wings, but just these guys on the ground and easily visible at the time. Sparrows hop along the ground, robins run, and grackles STALK, very tall and deliberate, and the pale eyes add to the menacing mini velociraptor impression. Super glossy and iridescent, so these are probably all males, but I have read that in some local varieties the females are less brown and nearly as shiny, so not necessarily a slam dunk. I wanted to try and record the stereotypical “rusty gate” calls to post a sound clip observation, but the ones in the bushes who were singing kept hushing up whenever I would press record on my phone. I’ll get them eventually…
Locked in

This is contestant #1, the first (and last) bird you hear in the audio clip. This is a prime spot for them every year, because the acoustics here make them VERY loud (instead of just LOUD like they usually are), something about the nearby buildings and parking lots I assume, and the fact that these trees have the open river on one side and a path/grassy area on the other mean they’re visually prominent as well. 

Still on autofocus and it was an extremely bright sunny morning, so I did have to edit these to decrease the contrast from being back-lit, and then try to tone down the resulting over-saturation, but for someone who doesn’t really know what she’s doing yet photographically, I was pretty happy with how they came out, and also excited to catch some more relatively clear audio.

(Update, the second bird is here: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/202133868)

Contestant number 2! This is the second bird you hear on the recording, whose call ends with a note that descends in pitch. The entry for the other guy is here: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/202133694

I forgot to take note if his song was recognizably one of the two from the morning before, which were distinct enough to tell apart. 

The males always show up early and make themselves conspicuous by being loud and flashy - I have a goal for the summer to get good photos of a quiet brown female and/or some babies. This is a pretty popular territory for them every year so it should be achievable.

description: Not great pics but adding to remember the way these guys were deliberately rushing people for kicks on the Museum campus, near the snack vendors. I’ve seen folks on the Chicago reddit complaining about RWBs diving at them, but the ones local to me are just very loud and will “Check!” from the bushes, but only chase one another or other birds. I don’t know if they’re just extra territorial downtown or if they’ve learned that children and some adults will accidentally drop their food if startled? But saw them a couple times in a row wait on the path until someone was close enough and then explosively fly up towards their face, causing several kids to yell and jump back. It actually WAS kind of amusing, and they aren’t corvids but maybe they just think it’s funny? Last three pictures: he jumped up and scared a small child, then perched on the trash can, then took off and came at ME and flew within inches of my face. Very unfortunate for him that I was taking photos and laughing instead of flinching and dropping snacks (sadly unable to get closer pics of him in flight, just had my phone out while sitting down to get a drink).

description:
Angry mama blackbird! Plenty of people were walking, biking, and jogging along the path, some even with dogs, but I was the only one being SUSPICIOUS, walking slowly and peering into the bushes, so I was the only one she tried to chase away. She was entirely correct, I *WAS* hoping to find her nest and see some baby blackbirds! Alas, I did not.
She kept landing on the railing, yelling at me, then taking off and flying at my head/almost making contact with my hat, before retreating into cover in the big shrub in the back. Repeat. Eventually dad came to see what the fuss was (last photo, can barely see him). These are actually a combo of taken on the way north to look for kingfishers/other interesting creatures and then back south instead of continuing up to Horner Park. The 5-6 minutes to get to the bend in the bridge and turn around were not enough for her to forget and let me be! I didn’t want to stress her out so I didn’t stay long, but if she had been a little more chill, I never would’ve suspected blackbird fledglings could be near to start with and would’ve spent way less time trying to see them!

This bird has faint traces of prominent gape corners still visible, so I’m pretty sure this is an older fledgling hanging out with the other kids, and not just a female. (Old enough that no overprotective parent came and harassed me!)

I knew this guy on the railing was a baby even from a distance even from the back, because he started crouching and fluttering and begging before I even noticed the mom flying in with bug delivery. (Last few photos, I skipped to the best one for the main image.) Child, you seem entirely big enough to start foraging on your own, but you can’t even eat bugs without dropping one and your mom having to catch it and give it to you again! If you just saw the second photo, you’d think the baby was feeding the mom!
